Here is how you to play the game of DREIDEL for Hanukkah! 

Start with a few pieces of gelt for each person, and some in the center pot.

Take a turn spinning the dreidel.

If the dreidel lands on:
‎ג - gimmel - take the whole pot!

‎נ - nun - nothing happens

‎ ה - hey- take half the pot

ש - shin - put one piece into the pot

Players are out when they run out of pieces and the winner is the last person standing with all the gelt!

Save this for Purim! Here is THE recipe:

Ingredients:
2/3 cup butter
1/2 cup sugar
1 egg
1 tsp. vanilla
1 tsp. lemon zest
1 tsp. baking powder
pinch salt
2 cups (+extra for rolling out dough) flour

Instructions:
Preheat oven to 375 F and prepare a baking sheet with parchment paper.
Cream butter and sugar about 1 minute.
Add egg, vanilla and the zest of a half a lemon and mix for another minute.
In a separate bowl, combine baking powder, salt, and 2 cups of the flour.
Combine the dry and wet ingredients.
Gather dough into a flat disk, use extra flour on your hands to make sure the dough is not sticky. Cover in plastic wrap and refrigerate 30-45 minutes.
Sprinkle working surface with flour, and roll out dough to 1/8-inch thick.
Use a circle cookie cutter (about 2-3 inch. in size) to cut circles in the dough.
Lift each circle off the surface and place on baking sheet.
Drop about a tsp. of filling onto each circle.
Pinch the circle into a three cornered triangle. Use water on your fingertips if the dough isn’t sticking.
Bake for 10 minutes at 375 degrees, take out just before edges brown.
Enjoy!

THIS IS IT! This is the recipe to use for baking hamentashen cookies for Purim this year!

Ingredients:
2/3 cup butter
1/2 cup sugar
1 egg
1 tsp. vanilla
1 tsp. lemon zest
1 tsp. baking powder
pinch salt
2 cups (+extra for rolling out dough) flour

Instructions:
Preheat oven to 375 F and prepare a baking sheet with parchment paper.
Cream butter and sugar about 1 minute.
Add egg, vanilla and the zest of a half a lemon and mix for another minute.
In a separate bowl, combine baking powder, salt, and 2 cups of the flour.
Combine the dry and wet ingredients.
Gather dough into a flat disk, use extra flour on your hands to make sure the dough is not sticky. Cover in plastic wrap and refrigerate 30-45 minutes.
Sprinkle working surface with flour, and roll out dough to 1/8-inch thick.
Use a circle cookie cutter (about 2-3 inch. in size) to cut circles in the dough.
Lift each circle off the surface and place on baking sheet.
Drop about a tsp. of filling onto each circle.
Pinch the circle into a three cornered triangle. Use water on your fingertips if the dough isn’t sticking.
Bake for 10 minutes at 375 degrees, take out just before edges brown.
Enjoy!

There are many symbolic objects on our Seder table, and the Seder plate is the central one.

On it there is an egg 🥚 to symbolize the fertility and hope of Springtime. There are fresh greens like parsley 🌿 to remind us of the newness of the season. There is a shank-bone 🍗 which represents the sacrificial lamb, the offering Jews brought to our ancient Temple during the Pesach (Passover) holiday. There are bitter herbs 🥬 (sometimes there are two different types on the Seder plate), which are meant to taste like the bitterness of slavery. The charoset 🍎 mixture resembles the mortar used by the Jewish people to build the ancient pyramids.

We look at the matzah 🫓 on our table and think ‘ha lachma anya’ - ‘this is the bread of our affliction’. Tonight we will taste the bitterness of our enslavement and the desperate hurry we were in to be free as though each of us tonight were redeemed from slavery.

Matzo Pizza THREE ways! In just 20 minutes I stocked up my freezer with two different and delicious matzo pizzas and one extra super simple one! Save this reel so you have the recipe details ready to go when you’re ready to think about a quick family friendly Passover meal!

Matzo Farfel Kugel Recipe
3 cups farfel
1 cup vege soup broth
1 egg
Pizza seasoning spices of your choice
1 jar pizza sauce
1 8 oz. bag of shredded mozzarella cheese

Mix the farfel, broth, spices and egg together, add more broth if the mixture is too dry and not sticking together and add extra farfel if it’s too wet and you can clearly see liquid. Next layer on sauce and cheese. Bake at 350F for 30 minutes or freeze and have it ready to go!

Matzo Lasagna 
This recipe is from @fun.in.the.bc 

1/2 box matzo
1 jar pasta sauce
1 15 oz. tub of ricotta cheese
1 8 oz. bag of shredded mozzarella cheese

Mix the pasta sauce and ricotta together, then layer a lasagna pan starting with sauce, then one layer of matzo, more sauce, more matzo and then cheese up until you’ve filled your pan. End with the cheese so it has a delicious top. Bake at 375F for about 35 minutes until cheese crust is golden brown or freeze and have it ready to go!

And for the simplest matzo pizza just add sauce to a piece of matzo and bake at 375F for about 10 minutes watching it doesn’t burn.

Enjoy!!

What do I think about people who convert to Judaism? ⁣

I get asked this question a lot. A lot more than I ever thought I would. I never once even considered this question until I launched my YouTube channel. I assumed it was a given. I think Jewish people who convert are exactly the same as Jewish people who were born Jewish, and born Orthodox, or Reform or Conservative or unaffiliated or questioning (aren't we all at times!). Our souls were all there at Mt. Sinai ⛰when God handed us the Torah and it is up to each of us to decide what to do with it. ⁣

Tonight begins the Jewish holiday of Shavuot and it celebrates the receiving of the 10 Commandments. Each year on this holiday we read the story of Ruth, who recites this beautiful line when she says to the family she has chosen that she won't leave them now that her Jewish husband has died, her love and commitment to them and this faith is beyond that. 'Wherever you go, I will go.'. ⁣

We read this story each year to remind us that many things will come up that will easily throw us off our path and we don't need to stay the course, but we can choose to. So whether you made that choice in adulthood, whether you never realized you were making it but de facto made it anyways, whether you are still deciding, we're all in the midst of this decision always and we're all equal.⁣

Then the angels thought maybe the bottom of the sea would be a better place, but they realized that one day man would figure out how to swim. Then, a very shrewd angel suggested they put this spark in the human’s own heart, because man will never look for it there. So God listened, he took this infinitely powerful spark and put it so deep that we can’t find it alone. 

I hope you are all able to find love and be loved by those who see the Divine spark within you.

Do you remember learning about the real miracle of Hanukkah? It wasn’t just about oil, it was about how a the Maccabees fought to protect our ancient and holy temple in Jerusalem 160 BCE! This year, over 2000 years later, I want my children to see that they are part of the continuing story of miracles 🕎.

Here are the 3 things I want to teach my children this year about this special holiday:⁣
⁣
1. It’s OK to believe in miracles.⁣

There are many miracles in the story of Hanukkah. When the Maccabee’s triumph over tyranny, when the oil lasts for eight days, when the Holy Temple is restored...through each of these events we learn not to let the light of hope go ⁣out.⁣
⁣
⁣2. The Maccabees were a small group of rebels who saw the injustice of not being able to live their true identity.⁣
⁣
They banded together in their fight for justice and achieved an unimaginable victory against a powerful oppressive leader.⁣
⁣
3. In the darkness remember that you are a descendant of the Maccabees, and you can kindle a light.⁣
⁣
In the story of Hanukkah we see how we have the divine power to make light in the darkness.⁣
⁣
Our own light is never diminished when we share it with others, if anything it grows. When you feel in your own darkest place, try to do one act of ‘tikkun’ one good deed and see how your own light grows.⁣

Here is how you to play the game of DREIDEL for Hanukkah! 

Start by dividing up the gelt with a few pieces for each person, and some in the center pot. You can also play with coins or nuts!

Take a turn spinning the dreidel.

If the dreidel lands on:

‎ג - gimmel - take the whole center pot!

‎נ - nun - nothing happens

‎ ה - hey- take half the pot

‎ש - shin - put one piece into the pot

Players are out when they run out of pieces and the winner is the last person standing with all the gelt!
